{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613988"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:41:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:41:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16337"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16337"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9028"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116455"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9028"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16337"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98454"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7519"},{"type":"tags","id":"7531"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21475"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21480"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116455"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe retina is the light-sensitive neural layer of the eye that converts light into electrical signals for visual processing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical features of the retina?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Extends from optic nerve anteriorly to ora serrata posteriorly","Outer retina receives blood supply from central retinal vessels","Fovea centralis contains lowest density of cone photoreceptors","Macula contains highest density of cone photoreceptors","Retina lacks a basement membrane structure"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emacula contains the highest density of cone photoreceptors\u003C/strong\u003E, particularly in the fovea centralis, which is responsible for high-resolution central vision. This dense concentration of cones enables detailed colour vision and fine visual discrimination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe retina \u003Cstrong\u003Eextends from optic nerve anteriorly to ora serrata posteriorly\u003C/strong\u003E - this statement reverses the correct anatomical orientation, as the retina extends from the optic nerve posteriorly to the ora serrata anteriorly. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eouter retina receives blood supply from central retinal vessels\u003C/strong\u003E - the outer retina is actually supplied by the choroidal circulation. The \u003Cstrong\u003Efovea centralis contains lowest density of cone photoreceptors\u003C/strong\u003E - the fovea actually contains the highest density of cones. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eretina lacks a basement membrane structure\u003C/strong\u003E - the retina has several basement membranes, including Bruch\u0027s membrane.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe macula is approximately 5.5 mm in diameter and is located temporal to the optic disc. The fovea centralis, at the centre of the macula, contains the highest concentration of cone photoreceptors in the retina.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The retina extends from the optic nerve posteriorly to the ora serrata anteriorly.","The macula contains the highest density of cone photoreceptors, particularly in the fovea centralis, enabling high-resolution central vision.","The outer retina receives its blood supply from the choroidal circulation, while the inner retina is supplied by the central retinal vessels."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98454"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16337"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98454"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T10:16:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T10:18:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9028"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116455"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationsh